 *
 * The validate method returns `true` if the entire sudoku table is valid, `false` otherwise.
 * Expected input for this function is a variable number of Arrays, where each array
 * represents one row of a sudoku table.
 *
 * For example you could expect something like this for a valid table:
 *
 * [
 * [2,9,5,7,4,3,8,6,1],
 * [4,3,1,8,6,5,9,2,7],
 * [8,7,6,1,9,2,5,4,3],
 * [3,8,7,4,5,9,2,1,6],
 * [6,1,2,3,8,7,4,9,5],
 * [5,4,9,2,1,6,7,3,8],
 * [7,6,3,5,2,4,1,8,9],
 * [9,2,8,6,7,1,3,5,4],
 * [1,5,4,9,3,8,6,7,2]
 * ]
 *
 * http://imgur.com/a/Vuvss
 *
 * Sudoku Rules:
 * • Each cell can be empty or contain a single number from 1-9
 * • Each row (red) cannot have cells with duplicate values (unless the cell is empty)
 * • Each column (yellow) cannot have cells with duplicate values (unless the cell is empty)
 * • Each region (blue) cannot have cells with duplicate values (unless the cell is empty)
 *
 * @params board an array of arrays, where each array element represents a row in a sudoku table
 * @return true if the Sudoku table contains valid values, false otherwise.
 */

const uniq = require('lodash/uniq');

const isValidNumber = (rawValue) => {
  const number = parseInt(rawValue, 10);
  return number && number >= 1 && number <= 9;
};

const isBlockValid = (block) => {
  if (block.length !== 9) return false;

  const validNumbers = block.filter(n => isValidNumber(n));
  const uniqValidNumbers = uniq(validNumbers);

  return uniqValidNumbers.length === validNumbers.length;
};

const transpose = arr => arr[0].map((col, i) => arr.map(row => row[i]));

const getGrids = (matrix) => {
  const grids = [];

  // not using i++ because eslint's no-plusplus rule
  for (let i = 0; i < 9; i += 1) {
    for (let j = 0; j < 9; j += 1) {
      const x = Math.floor(i / 3);
      const y = Math.floor(j / 3);

      const index = (x * 3) + y;

      if (!Array.isArray(grids[index])) {
        grids[index] = [];
      }

      grids[index].push(matrix[i][j]);
    }
  }

  return grids;
};

function validate(boardJSON) {
  /**
   * There are 2 reasons behind using try/catch:
   * - checking if provided JSON string is valid. (JSON.parse will throw an error if it's not)
   * - breaking forEach loops as soon as we detect an error.
   */

  try {
    const rows = JSON.parse(boardJSON);
    const cols = transpose(rows);
    const grids = getGrids(rows);

    // Validate each cell in the matrix
    rows.forEach(row => row.forEach((cell) => {
      if (cell !== null && !isValidNumber(cell)) {
        throw Error('Invalid Number');
      }
    }));

    // Validate blocks
    [...rows, ...cols, ...grids].forEach((block) => {
      if (!isBlockValid(block)) {
        throw Error('Invalid block');
      }
    });
  } catch (e) {
    return false;
  }

  return true;
}


/** **********************************************************************************
 *
 *                    TESTING CODE BELOW
 *
 ************************************************************************************/

const util = require('util');
const puzzledBoards64 = '';

const loopIt = new Map(JSON.parse(Buffer.from(puzzledBoards64, 'base64')));

let total = 0;
let passed = 0;
for (const set of loopIt) {
  total++;
  const str = set[1];

  const res = validate(str);

  if (res == set[0][1]) {
    console.log(util.format('%s, ✔ expected %s, returned %s', set[0][0], set[0][1], res));
    passed++;
  } else {
    console.log(util.format('%s, ✖ expected %s, returned %s', set[0][0], set[0][1], res));
  }
}

console.log('===============================================');
console.log(util.format('Overall result : %s out of %s passed validation', passed, total));
console.log('');
